==English==
===Etymology===
Uncertain.  Perhaps a pun on the [[Melbourne]] [[department store]] [[w:Buckley and Nunn|Buckley and Nunn]].  Perhaps derived from [[Buckley's chance]].  (Reference: Bill Wannan, ''Australian Folklore'', Lansdowne Press, 1970, reprint 1979 ISBN 0-7018-1309-1, entry for "Buckley's Chance".)
===Noun===
'''[[Buckley's]] [[and]] [[none]]'''
# {{AU}} {{colloquial}} A supposed two chances (probabilities), being [[Buckley's chance]] (meaning a very small chance) or no chance at all.